## Documentation Resources

### Official Resources

- **[cppreference.com](https://en.cppreference.com/)** - Most comprehensive C++ reference covering C++11 through C++23
- **[ISO C++ Official Site](https://isocpp.org/)** - Official C++ standards information, FAQ, and guidelines
- **[C++ Core Guidelines](https://isocpp.github.io/CppCoreGuidelines/CppCoreGuidelines)** - Best practices by Bjarne Stroustrup and Herb Sutter
- **[C++ Standard Draft](https://eel.is/c++draft/)** - Latest working draft of the standard

### Learning Resources

- **[LearnCpp.com](https://www.learncpp.com/)** - Comprehensive tutorials
- **[Refactoring Guru](https://refactoring.guru/design-patterns/cpp)** - Design Patterns with C++ examples
- **[SourceMaking](https://sourcemaking.com/design_patterns)** - Design patterns and UML
- **[Compiler Explorer](https://godbolt.org/)** - Online compiler for testing and experimentation

---

## Getting Started

1. **Start with Course 1** if you're new to C++ - covers fundamentals from basic syntax to STL
2. **Move to Course 2** to learn structural design patterns for better code organization
3. **Progress to Course 3** for advanced features and modern C++ practices

Use the links provided to reference official documentation as you learn!

